{"title_page": "Taiwan Travel Act", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|United States law allowing official high-level relations between the U.S. and Taiwanese governments}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n|shorttitle        = Taiwan Travel Act\n|othershorttitles  = \n|longtitle         = An act to encourage visits between the United States and Taiwan at all levels, and for other purposes.\n|colloquialacronym = TTA\n|nickname          = \n|enacted by        = 115th\n|effective date    = \n|cite public law   = {{USPL|115|135}}\n|cite statutes at large = \n|acts amended    = \n|acts repealed   = \n|title amended   = \n|sections created = \n|sections amended = \n|leghisturl      = https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/535\n|introducedin    = House\n|introducedbill  = {{USBill|115|H.R.|535}}\n|introducedby    = [[Steve Chabot]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Ohio|OH]])\n|introduceddate  = January 13, 2017\n|committees      = [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs]], [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations]]\n|passedbody1     = House\n|passeddate1     = January 9, 2018\n|passedvote1     = Voice vote\n|passedbody2     = Senate\n|passeddate2     = February 28, 2018\n|passedvote2     = Unanimous consent\n|signedpresident = [[Donald Trump]]\n|signeddate      = March 16, 2018\n|unsignedpresident = \n|unsigneddate    = \n|vetoedpresident = \n|vetoeddate      = \n|overriddenbody1 = \n|overriddendate1 = \n|overriddenvote1 = \n|overriddenbody2 = \n|overriddendate2 = \n|overriddenvote2 = \n|amendments      = \n|SCOTUS cases    = \n}}\nThe '''Taiwan Travel Act''' ({{USBill|115|H.R.|535}}, {{USPL|115|135}}) is an [[Act of Congress|Act]] of the [[United States Congress]]. Passed on February 28, 2018, it was signed into law by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] on March 16, 2018.<ref name=\"taipei times\">{{cite news|date=2 March 2018|title=US Senate passes Taiwan Travel Act|url=http://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/03/02/2003688517|work=[[Taipei Times]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> As a follow-up to the [[Taiwan Relations Act]], the bill allows high-level officials of the [[United States]] to visit [[Taiwan]] and vice versa.\n\nThe law is considered a substantial upgrade to [[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]], making them official though still sub-[[Diplomacy|diplomatic]].  As such, the law was harshly criticized by the government of the [[People's Republic of China]] in Beijing (which had formally protested the bill through ambassador [[Cui Tiankai|Cui Tiankai]], demanding it not pass) for violating the [[One-China policy|One-China principle]], which holds that Taiwan is an inalienable sovereign part of China.  Although it does not refer to the government of Taiwan by a name, the Act significantly upgrades relations between the United States and the [[History of the Republic of China|Republic of China]], which governs Taiwan.\n\nIn July 2019 Taiwanese President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] used this act to travel freely to New York City, New York and [[Denver, Colorado]] while in transit to countries in the Caribbean that still have official diplomatic relations with Taiwan. Before the act was passed Taiwanese presidents usually could only meet local Texas government officials in Houston, Texas, which is where he or she could get on transit flights to the Caribbean and South America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/01/09/against-chinas-objections-ted-cruz-and-texas-governor-meet-with-taiwanese-president/|title=Against China's objections, Ted Cruz and Texas governor meet with Taiwanese president|first=Amy B. Wang closeAmy B. WangNational politics reporter covering 2020 presidential|last=campaignsEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowReporter|website=Washington Post}}</ref> Tsai was the first Taiwanese president to visit UN ambassadors of Taiwan's diplomatic allies in New York since the passage of the Taiwan Relations Act in 1979. In New York she also met with a U.S. congressional delegation headed by [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs#List of chairmen|U.S. House Foreign Affairs Chairman]] [[Eliot Engel]] (D-NY) and Ranking Member [[Michael McCaul]] (R-TX). In Denver she met with the governor of Colorado, some U.S. congressmembers and mayors from the local area and visited the [[National Center for Atmospheric Research]] and the [[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gop-foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/bipartisan-congressional-delegation-meets-taiwan-president-tsai-in-new-york/|title=Bipartisan Congressional Delegation Meets Taiwan President Tsai in New York}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/07/21/2003719057|title=Tsai tells Denver group: Nation 'will not succumb' - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|date=July 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Further information|Chinese Civil War|Cross-Strait relations|Two Chinas}}\n\nWhen the U.S. established diplomatic relations with the [[People's Republic of China]] in 1979, it also ceased to officially recognize Taiwan but continued to maintain unofficial relations with the island.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|last=Bodeen|first=Christopher|date=2 March 2018|title=China Lashes Out at U.S. Over Loosening of Taiwan Travel Rules|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-02/china-lashes-out-at-us-over-loosening-of-taiwan-travel-rules|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> In the same year, the U.S. enacted the [[Taiwan Relations Act]].<ref name=\"taipei times2\">{{cite news|date=11 January 2018|title=US House passes Taiwan Travel Act|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/01/11/2003685572|work=Taipei Times|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Taiwan Travel Act was introduced to the U.S. Congress by Representative [[Steve Chabot]] and Senator [[Marco Rubio]];<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/03/us-paves-way-for-high-level-exchanges-with-taiwan/|title=US Paves Way for High-Level Exchanges With Taiwan|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=3 March 2018|work=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> part of the [[House Foreign Relations Committee]] and the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], respectively.<ref name=\":0\" />  The bill was considered a follow-up to the Taiwan Relations Act and stated that the U.S. and Taiwan had suffered from insufficient high-level communication since 1979, when the U.S. started to restrict its officials' visits to Taiwan.<ref name=\"taipei times2\"/>\n\n=== Chinese pressure on Congress ===\nIn August 2017, [[Cui Tiankai]], the [[Chinese Ambassador to United States|Chinese Ambassador]] to the United States, sent a letter expressing \"grave concern\" to leaders of the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] and [[United States Senate|Senate]], demanding they block provisions related to Taiwan in the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2018|National Defense Authorization Act]] of that year, which included the Taiwan Travel Act as well as the [[Taiwan Security Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"washington post\">{{cite web|last=Rogin|first=Josh|date=12 October 2017|title=China threatens U.S. Congress for crossing its 'red line' on Taiwan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2017/10/12/china-threatens-u-s-congress-for-crossing-its-red-line-on-taiwan/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  In the letter, Ambassador Cui stated the legislation together with another bill ({{As of|2018|December|alt=that has not passed|df=|lc=|since=}}) represent \u201cprovocations against China\u2019s sovereignty, national unity and security interests,\u201d and \u201chave crossed the \u2018[[Red line (phrase)|red line]]\u2019 on the stability of the [[China\u2013United States relations|China-U.S. relationship]]\u201d. US lawmakers perceived this wording, together with the Chinese threat of \u201csevere consequences\u201d as inappropriate interference and \"out of line\".<ref name=\"washington post\" /><ref name=\"diplomat\" />\n\n==== American responses ====\n\n\nOne Democratic aide said: \u201cMaking these sorts of threats and laying down \u2018red lines\u2019 on domestic legislative action is neither helpful or constructive to build the sort of relationship needed between the United States and China.\u201d<ref name=\"washington post\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' journalist [[Josh Rogin]] noted:<blockquote>Other congressional aides said that no other embassy uses threats as a tactic to influence Congress, especially not via an official communication. Most embassies try to build relationships and persuade U.S. policymakers to support what they believe is in their [[national interest]]. But not China.<ref name=\"washington post\" /></blockquote>Ranking House Foreign Affairs Committee [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Eliot Engel]] (D-NY) said in response:<blockquote>\u201cChina carries out this kind of heavy-handed behavior with other countries around the world.  It\u2019s interesting to me that they now feel that they can get away with these kind of threats and vague pressure tactics with the U.S. Congress.\u201d<ref name=\"washington post\" /></blockquote>It has been suggested that China's heavy-handed tactics and direct threats to United States Congress through official communications [[Unintended consequences|backfired]], by forcing Congress to make a [[show of force]] against perceived Chinese bullying.<ref name=\"diplomat\" />  This affected the unanimous passage of the law.\n\n=== Congressional delegation to Taiwan in September 2018 ===\nIn September 2018, House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman [[Ed Royce]] led a bipartisan delegation of US lawmakers to Taiwan, where he was awarded the Republic of China (Taiwan)'s [[Order of Brilliant Star]] with Special Grand Cordon from [[President of the Republic of China|President]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] for his \"outstanding contributions to Taiwan's development\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/search/201709010013.aspx|title=President confers medal on U.S. Congressman Ed Royce|date=2017-09-01|website=[[Focus Taiwan]]|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/chairman-royce-meets-president-tsai-taiwan/|title=Chairman Royce Meets with President Tsai in Taiwan|website=Committee on Foreign Affairs|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref>  Royce had previously been awarded the Order of Brilliant Star with Grand Cordon in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201503130037.aspx|title=President confers medal on U.S. congressman for supporting Taiwan|last1=Huang|first1=Kelven|date=13 March 2015|accessdate=14 March 2015|last2=Hou|first2=Elaine}}</ref>\n\nUpon receiving his accolade from President Tsai on September 1st, Royce said:<blockquote>\u201cI am honored to receive the Order of Brilliant Star with Special Grand Cordon and view it as a symbol of the [[Special relationship (international relations)|special bonds]] between the U.S. and Taiwan. I want to thank President Tsai for receiving me today, and for her commitment to making the partnership between our two peoples even stronger \u2013 a commitment I share. Taiwan is one of our most important friends in the [[Asia-Pacific|Asia Pacific]] region, and our partnership is anchored in a shared commitment to [[Democracy|democratic values]].</blockquote><blockquote>\u201cAs a [[Free society|free]] and democratic society, Taiwan is an example to its neighbors in the Asia Pacific. Its economy is diverse and growing, which means there is great potential for increased economic ties. The United States will remain steadfast in its commitments to Taiwan\u2019s security. The Taiwan Relations Act and the Six Assurances make it clear that a stable, free, and prosperous Taiwan is in America\u2019s national security interests.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Legislative history==\nOn {{Format date|2017|October|12}}, the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|U.S. House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] passed the bill with no opposition.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/foreign-affairs-committee-passes-taiwan-travel-act/|title=Foreign Affairs Committee Passes Taiwan Travel Act|website=Committee on Foreign Affairs|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><ref name=\"diplomat\">{{cite news|last=Charlotte|first=Gao|date=17 October 2017|title=China's Lobbying Against the Taiwan Travel Act Backfires|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/10/chinas-lobbying-against-the-taiwan-travel-act-backfires/|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Committee Chairman Ed Royce explained:<blockquote>Currently, the State Department enforces self-imposed restrictions on official travel between the U.S. and Taiwan. This bill denounces that practice by encouraging more frequent [[State visit|official visits]] \u2013 including at the highest levels \u2013 and will serve to further strengthen the critical U.S.-Taiwan partnership. This bill builds off legislation we passed out of the committee last month, which addressed Taiwan\u2019s exclusion from the [[World Health Assembly]].<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>The following day on {{Format date|2017|October|13}}, a spokesperson for China's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] commented:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1501588.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Hua Chunying's Regular Press Conference on October 13, 2017|website=www.fmprc.gov.cn|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><blockquote>The Chinese side urges the US side to comply with the [[one-China policy]] and the principles of the [[Three Communiqu\u00e9s|three China-US joint communiques]] and cautiously handle [[Political status of Taiwan|the Taiwan question]], not to engage in any official exchange and contact with Taiwan or send any wrong message to the \"[[Taiwan independence movement|Taiwan independence]]\" separatists lest the larger picture of the China-US relations should be disrupted and undermined.</blockquote>In January 2018, the bill was passed unanimously by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"scmp\">{{cite news|date=1 March 2018|title=US Senate passes Taiwan travel bill slammed by China|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2135192/us-senate-passes-taiwan-travel-bill-slammed-china|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, it was also passed unanimously by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on February 28.<ref name=\"taipei times\"/>  President Donald Trump signed the Act into law on March 16, 2018.<ref name=\"taipei times\" />\n\n==Provisions==\nProvisions of the Taiwan Travel Act state that the U.S. should:<ref name=\"senate\">{{cite web|date=4 May 2017|title=S.1051 - Taiwan Travel Act|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/1051|work=United States Congress|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n*Allow officials at all levels of the U.S. government to travel to Taiwan to meet their Taiwanese counterparts;\n*Allow high-level Taiwanese officials to enter the United States under respectful conditions and to meet with U.S. officials;\n*Encourage the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office]] and any other instrumentality established by Taiwan to conduct business in the United States.\n\n==Reaction==\n===Taiwan===\nIn January 2018, [[President of the Republic of China|Taiwanese President]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] expressed her gratitude to the U.S. Congress for \"supporting Taiwan\u2019s democracy\" through her [[Twitter]] account, stating she believed the Taiwan Travel Act would \"strengthen and enhance the long-standing partnership between the two sides.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\">{{cite news|date=11 January 2018|title=MOFA thanks US House for passing two bills supporting Taiwan|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3339114|work=[[Taiwan News]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Taiwan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] also showed its support for the bill, saying Taiwan was \"committed to fostering an upgraded [[strategic partnership]] with the U.S.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\"/>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\nThe Chinese state-controlled ''[[Xinhua News Agency]]'' indicated that China was \"strongly dissatisfied\" with the bill and said it violated the [[one-China policy]] that asserts Taiwan is a province of China.<ref name=\"scmp\"/>\n\nThe Chinese [[Media of China#Communist Party control|state-run]] ''[[Global Times]]'' quoted professor Li Haidong at the [[China Foreign Affairs University]] that \"the U.S.' irresponsible move increas[ed] uncertainty and risks for bilateral ties and revers[ed] the gears of a stable and positive [[Sino\u2013American relations|Sino-US relationship]].\"<ref name=\"global times\">{{cite news|last=Li|first=Ruohan|date=1 March 2018|title=China could respond to Taiwan Travel Act with Anti-Secession Law|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1091393.shtml|work=[[Global Times]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Li also held that the [[Anti-Secession Law]] of China could be used to counter Washington's move, effectively referring to a threat of military seizure of Taiwan in the event of a unilateral Taiwanese declaration of [[Taiwanese Independence|independence]].<ref name=\"global times\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taiwan Relations Act]]\n*[[Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative Act|TAIPEI Act]]\n*[[Six Assurances]]\n*[[Political status of Taiwan]]\n*{{Section link|Foreign relations of Taiwan|United States}}\n*[[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n*[[China\u2013United States relations]]\n*[[Cross-Strait relations]]\n*[[Two Chinas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of the United States}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Acts of the 115th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:2018 in American law]]\n[[Category:Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|United States law allowing official high-level relations between the U.S. and Taiwanese governments}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n|shorttitle        = Taiwan Travel Act\n|othershorttitles  = \n|longtitle         = An act to encourage visits between the United States and Taiwan at all levels, and for other purposes.\n|colloquialacronym = TTA\n|nickname          = \n|enacted by        = 115th\n|effective date    = \n|cite public law   = {{USPL|115|135}}\n|cite statutes at large = \n|acts amended    = \n|acts repealed   = \n|title amended   = \n|sections created = \n|sections amended = \n|leghisturl      = https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/535\n|introducedin    = House\n|introducedbill  = {{USBill|115|H.R.|535}}\n|introducedby    = [[Steve Chabot]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Ohio|OH]])\n|introduceddate  = January 13, 2017\n|committees      = [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs]], [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations]]\n|passedbody1     = House\n|passeddate1     = January 9, 2018\n|passedvote1     = Voice vote\n|passedbody2     = Senate\n|passeddate2     = February 28, 2018\n|passedvote2     = Unanimous consent\n|signedpresident = [[Donald Trump]]\n|signeddate      = March 16, 2018\n|unsignedpresident = \n|unsigneddate    = \n|vetoedpresident = \n|vetoeddate      = \n|overriddenbody1 = \n|overriddendate1 = \n|overriddenvote1 = \n|overriddenbody2 = \n|overriddendate2 = \n|overriddenvote2 = \n|amendments      = \n|SCOTUS cases    = \n}}\nThe '''Taiwan Travel Act''' ({{USBill|115|H.R.|535}}, {{USPL|115|135}}) is an [[Act of Congress|Act]] of the [[United States Congress]]. Passed on February 28, 2018, it was signed into law by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] on March 16, 2018.<ref name=\"taipei times\">{{cite news|date=2 March 2018|title=US Senate passes Taiwan Travel Act|url=http://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/03/02/2003688517|work=[[Taipei Times]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> As a follow-up to the [[Taiwan Relations Act]], the bill allows high-level officials of the [[United States]] to visit [[Taiwan]] and vice versa.\n\nThe law is considered a substantial upgrade to [[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]], making them official though still sub-[[Diplomacy|diplomatic]].  As such, the law was harshly criticized by the government of the [[People's Republic of China]] in Beijing (which had formally protested the bill through ambassador [[Cui Tiankai|Cui Tiankai]], demanding it not pass) for violating the [[One-China policy|One-China principle]], which holds that Taiwan is an inalienable sovereign part of China.  Although it does not refer to the government of Taiwan by a name, the Act significantly upgrades relations between the United States and the [[History of the Republic of China|Republic of China]], which governs Taiwan.\n\nIn July 2019 Taiwanese President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] used this act to travel freely to New York City, New York and [[Denver, Colorado]] while in transit to countries in the Caribbean that still have official diplomatic relations with Taiwan. Before the act was passed Taiwanese presidents usually could only meet local Texas government officials in Houston, Texas, which is where he or she could get on transit flights to the Caribbean and South America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/01/09/against-chinas-objections-ted-cruz-and-texas-governor-meet-with-taiwanese-president/|title=Against China's objections, Ted Cruz and Texas governor meet with Taiwanese president|first=Amy B. Wang closeAmy B. WangNational politics reporter covering 2020 presidential|last=campaignsEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowReporter|website=Washington Post}}</ref> Tsai was the first Taiwanese president to visit UN ambassadors of Taiwan's diplomatic allies in New York since the passage of the Taiwan Relations Act in 1979. In New York she also met with a U.S. congressional delegation headed by [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs#List of chairmen|U.S. House Foreign Affairs Chairman]] [[Eliot Engel]] (D-NY) and Ranking Member [[Michael McCaul]] (R-TX). In Denver she met with the governor of Colorado, some U.S. congressmembers and mayors from the local area and visited the [[National Center for Atmospheric Research]] and the [[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gop-foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/bipartisan-congressional-delegation-meets-taiwan-president-tsai-in-new-york/|title=Bipartisan Congressional Delegation Meets Taiwan President Tsai in New York}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/07/21/2003719057|title=Tsai tells Denver group: Nation 'will not succumb' - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|date=July 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Further information|Chinese Civil War|Cross-Strait relations|Two Chinas}}\n\nWhen the U.S. established diplomatic relations with the [[People's Republic of China]] in 1979, it also ceased to officially recognize Taiwan but continued to maintain unofficial relations with the island.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|last=Bodeen|first=Christopher|date=2 March 2018|title=China Lashes Out at U.S. Over Loosening of Taiwan Travel Rules|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-02/china-lashes-out-at-us-over-loosening-of-taiwan-travel-rules|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> In the same year, the U.S. enacted the [[Taiwan Relations Act]].<ref name=\"taipei times2\">{{cite news|date=11 January 2018|title=US House passes Taiwan Travel Act|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2018/01/11/2003685572|work=Taipei Times|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Taiwan Travel Act was introduced to the U.S. Congress by Representative [[Steve Chabot]] and Senator [[Marco Rubio]];<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/03/us-paves-way-for-high-level-exchanges-with-taiwan/|title=US Paves Way for High-Level Exchanges With Taiwan|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=3 March 2018|work=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> part of the [[House Foreign Relations Committee]] and the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], respectively.<ref name=\":0\" />  The bill was considered a follow-up to the Taiwan Relations Act and stated that the U.S. and Taiwan had suffered from insufficient high-level communication since 1979, when the U.S. started to restrict its officials' visits to Taiwan.<ref name=\"taipei times2\"/>\n\n=== Chinese pressure on Congress ===\nIn August 2017, [[Cui Tiankai]], the [[Chinese Ambassador to United States|Chinese Ambassador]] to the United States, sent a letter expressing \"grave concern\" to leaders of the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] and [[United States Senate|Senate]], demanding they block provisions related to Taiwan in the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2018|National Defense Authorization Act]] of that year, which included the Taiwan Travel Act as well as the [[Taiwan Security Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"washington post\">{{cite web|last=Rogin|first=Josh|date=12 October 2017|title=China threatens U.S. Congress for crossing its 'red line' on Taiwan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2017/10/12/china-threatens-u-s-congress-for-crossing-its-red-line-on-taiwan/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  In the letter, Ambassador Cui stated the legislation together with another bill ({{As of|2018|December|alt=that has not passed|df=|lc=|since=}}) represent \u201cprovocations against China\u2019s sovereignty, national unity and security interests,\u201d and \u201chave crossed the \u2018[[Red line (phrase)|red line]]\u2019 on the stability of the [[China\u2013United States relations|China-U.S. relationship]]\u201d. US lawmakers perceived this wording, together with the Chinese threat of \u201csevere consequences\u201d as inappropriate interference and \"out of line\".<ref name=\"washington post\" /><ref name=\"diplomat\" />\n\n==== American responses ====\n\n\nOne Democratic aide said: \u201cMaking these sorts of threats and laying down \u2018red lines\u2019 on domestic legislative action is neither helpful or constructive to build the sort of relationship needed between the United States and China.\u201d<ref name=\"washington post\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' journalist [[Josh Rogin]] noted:<blockquote>Other congressional aides said that no other embassy uses threats as a tactic to influence Congress, especially not via an official communication. Most embassies try to build relationships and persuade U.S. policymakers to support what they believe is in their [[national interest]]. But not China.<ref name=\"washington post\" /></blockquote>Ranking House Foreign Affairs Committee [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Eliot Engel]] (D-NY) said in response:<blockquote>\u201cChina carries out this kind of heavy-handed behavior with other countries around the world.  It\u2019s interesting to me that they now feel that they can get away with these kind of threats and vague pressure tactics with the U.S. Congress.\u201d<ref name=\"washington post\" /></blockquote>It has been suggested that China's heavy-handed tactics and direct threats to United States Congress through official communications [[Unintended consequences|backfired]], by forcing Congress to make a [[show of force]] against perceived Chinese bullying.<ref name=\"diplomat\" />  This affected the unanimous passage of the law.\n\n=== Congressional delegation to Taiwan in September 2018 ===\nIn September 2018, House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman [[Ed Royce]] led a bipartisan delegation of US lawmakers to Taiwan, where he was awarded the Republic of China (Taiwan)'s [[Order of Brilliant Star]] with Special Grand Cordon from [[President of the Republic of China|President]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] for his \"outstanding contributions to Taiwan's development\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/search/201709010013.aspx|title=President confers medal on U.S. Congressman Ed Royce|date=2017-09-01|website=[[Focus Taiwan]]|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/chairman-royce-meets-president-tsai-taiwan/|title=Chairman Royce Meets with President Tsai in Taiwan|website=Committee on Foreign Affairs|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref>  Royce had previously been awarded the Order of Brilliant Star with Grand Cordon in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201503130037.aspx|title=President confers medal on U.S. congressman for supporting Taiwan|last1=Huang|first1=Kelven|date=13 March 2015|accessdate=14 March 2015|last2=Hou|first2=Elaine}}</ref>\n\nUpon receiving his accolade from President Tsai on September 1st, Royce said:<blockquote>\u201cI am honored to receive the Order of Brilliant Star with Special Grand Cordon and view it as a symbol of the [[Special relationship (international relations)|special bonds]] between the U.S. and Taiwan. I want to thank President Tsai for receiving me today, and for her commitment to making the partnership between our two peoples even stronger \u2013 a commitment I share. Taiwan is one of our most important friends in the [[Asia-Pacific|Asia Pacific]] region, and our partnership is anchored in a shared commitment to [[Democracy|democratic values]].</blockquote><blockquote>\u201cAs a [[Free society|free]] and democratic society, Taiwan is an example to its neighbors in the Asia Pacific. Its economy is diverse and growing, which means there is great potential for increased economic ties. The United States will remain steadfast in its commitments to Taiwan\u2019s security. The Taiwan Relations Act and the Six Assurances make it clear that a stable, free, and prosperous Taiwan is in America\u2019s national security interests.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Legislative history==\nOn {{Format date|2017|October|12}}, the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|U.S. House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] passed the bill with no opposition.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/press-release/foreign-affairs-committee-passes-taiwan-travel-act/|title=Foreign Affairs Committee Passes Taiwan Travel Act|website=Committee on Foreign Affairs|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><ref name=\"diplomat\">{{cite news|last=Charlotte|first=Gao|date=17 October 2017|title=China's Lobbying Against the Taiwan Travel Act Backfires|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/10/chinas-lobbying-against-the-taiwan-travel-act-backfires/|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Committee Chairman Ed Royce explained:<blockquote>Currently, the State Department enforces self-imposed restrictions on official travel between the U.S. and Taiwan. This bill denounces that practice by encouraging more frequent [[State visit|official visits]] \u2013 including at the highest levels \u2013 and will serve to further strengthen the critical U.S.-Taiwan partnership. This bill builds off legislation we passed out of the committee last month, which addressed Taiwan\u2019s exclusion from the [[World Health Assembly]].<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>The following day on {{Format date|2017|October|13}}, a spokesperson for China's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] commented:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1501588.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Hua Chunying's Regular Press Conference on October 13, 2017|website=www.fmprc.gov.cn|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref><blockquote>The Chinese side urges the US side to comply with the [[one-China policy]] and the principles of the [[Three Communiqu\u00e9s|three China-US joint communiques]] and cautiously handle [[Political status of Taiwan|the Taiwan question]], not to engage in any official exchange and contact with Taiwan or send any wrong message to the \"[[Taiwan independence movement|Taiwan independence]]\" separatists lest the larger picture of the China-US relations should be disrupted and undermined.</blockquote>In January 2018, the bill was passed unanimously by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"scmp\">{{cite news|date=1 March 2018|title=US Senate passes Taiwan travel bill slammed by China|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2135192/us-senate-passes-taiwan-travel-bill-slammed-china|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, it was also passed unanimously by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on February 28.<ref name=\"taipei times\"/>  President Donald Trump signed the Act into law on March 16, 2018.<ref name=\"taipei times\" />\n\n==Provisions==\nProvisions of the Taiwan Travel Act state that the U.S. should:<ref name=\"senate\">{{cite web|date=4 May 2017|title=S.1051 - Taiwan Travel Act|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/1051|work=United States Congress|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n*Allow officials at all levels of the U.S. government to travel to Taiwan to meet their Taiwanese counterparts;\n*Allow high-level Taiwanese officials to enter the United States under respectful conditions and to meet with U.S. officials;\n*Encourage the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office]] and any other instrumentality established by Taiwan to conduct business in the United States.\n\n==Reaction==\n===Taiwan===\nIn January 2018, [[President of the Republic of China|Taiwanese President]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] expressed her gratitude to the U.S. Congress for \"supporting Taiwan\u2019s democracy\" through her [[Twitter]] account, stating she believed the Taiwan Travel Act would \"strengthen and enhance the long-standing partnership between the two sides.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\">{{cite news|date=11 January 2018|title=MOFA thanks US House for passing two bills supporting Taiwan|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3339114|work=[[Taiwan News]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Taiwan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] also showed its support for the bill, saying Taiwan was \"committed to fostering an upgraded [[strategic partnership]] with the U.S.\"<ref name=\"taiwan news\"/>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\nThe Chinese state-controlled ''[[Xinhua News Agency]]'' indicated that China was \"strongly dissatisfied\" with the bill and said it violated the [[one-China policy]] that asserts Taiwan is a province of China.<ref name=\"scmp\"/>\n\nThe Chinese [[Media of China#Communist Party control|state-run]] ''[[Global Times]]'' quoted professor Li Haidong at the [[China Foreign Affairs University]] that \"the U.S.' irresponsible move increas[ed] uncertainty and risks for bilateral ties and revers[ed] the gears of a stable and positive [[Sino\u2013American relations|Sino-US relationship]].\"<ref name=\"global times\">{{cite news|last=Li|first=Ruohan|date=1 March 2018|title=China could respond to Taiwan Travel Act with Anti-Secession Law|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1091393.shtml|work=[[Global Times]]|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>  Li also held that the [[Anti-Secession Law]] of China could be used to counter Washington's move, effectively referring to a threat of military seizure of Taiwan in the event of a unilateral Taiwanese declaration of [[Taiwanese Independence|independence]].<ref name=\"global times\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taiwan Relations Act]]\n*[[Six Assurances]]\n*[[Political status of Taiwan]]\n*{{Section link|Foreign relations of Taiwan|United States}}\n*[[Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n*[[China\u2013United States relations]]\n*[[Cross-Strait relations]]\n*[[Two Chinas]]\n*[[Taiwan Allies International Protection and Enhancement Initiative Act]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of the United States}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Acts of the 115th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:2018 in American law]]\n[[Category:Taiwan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n", "name_user": "Bokmanrocks01", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwan_Travel_Act"}
{"title_page": "2.02 (Buran-class spacecraft)", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=OK-2.02|2=Talk:Ptichka#Requested move 11 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Reusable launch system}}\n{{Infobox Space Shuttle | name = 2.02\n| image =\n| caption =\n| number =\n| country =[[Soviet Union]]\n| contract =1983\n| named_after =\n| first_flight =\n| first_date =\n| last_flight =\n| last_date =\n| missions =\n| crews =\n| time =None\n| orbits =\n| distance =\n| deployed =\n| dockings_mir =\n| dockings_iss =\n| status =Dismantled\n|}}\n\n'''2.02''' ([[GRAU]] index [[serial number]] 11F35 '''4K''') is the designation of the fourth built<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.k26.com/buran/Future/2.02/space_buran_2_02.html|title=Space Buran 2.02|first=k26 Design|last=Group|website=www.k26.com}}</ref> Soviet/Russian space shuttle orbiter to be produced as part of the [[Buran program]]. It was never officially named. \n\n==History==\nConstruction of 2.02 is believed to began in 1988. The spacecraft belong to the second series orbiters, whose design has been improved considering experience of flight of K1 Buran<ref>http://www.buran.ru/galapago/NK2018-12_buran.pdf</ref>.\n\nBy 1993, when the Buran program was cancelled, orbiter 2.02 was in an early stage of construction (10-20 percent)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buran-energia.com/bourane-buran/bourane-modele-202.php|title=Buran Built models OK-2.02|website=www.buran-energia.com}}</ref>. Only forward fuselage with crew cabin was completed. The incomplete 2.02 was later partially dismantled at its construction site and moved to the outside of the Tushino Machine Building Plant, near Moscow.\n\nRight wing with landing gear produced for this orbiter was used to complete 0.01 test article, now on display at [[Exhibition_of_Achievements_of_National_Economy|VDNKh]]<ref>http://www.buran.ru/other/NK2012-06_p_70-71.pdf</ref> \n\nSome of the tiles from orbiter 2.02 were sold and auctioned on the [[Internet]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[Buran_program|Buran program]]\n* [[Spaceplane]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.buran-energia.com/bourane-buran/bourane-modele-202.php 2.02 orbiter]\n* [http://www.k26.com/buran/Future/2.02/space_buran_2_02.html 2.02 current status]\n\n{{Russian manned space programs}}\n{{Buran program}}\n{{Space Shuttles}}\n\n[[Category:Buran program]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Soviet spacecraft]]\n[[Category: Individual space vehicles]]\n\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=OK-2.02|2=Talk:Ptichka#Requested move 11 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Reusable launch system}}\n{{Infobox Space Shuttle | name = 2.02\n| image =\n| caption =\n| number =\n| country =[[Soviet Union]]\n| contract =1983\n| named_after =\n| first_flight =\n| first_date =\n| last_flight =\n| last_date =\n| missions =\n| crews =\n| time =None\n| orbits =\n| distance =\n| deployed =\n| dockings_mir =\n| dockings_iss =\n| status =Dismantled\n|}}\n\n'''2.02''' ([[GRAU]] index [[serial number]] 11F35 '''4K''') is the designation of the fourth built<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.k26.com/buran/Future/2.02/space_buran_2_02.html|title=Space Buran 2.02|first=k26 Design|last=Group|website=www.k26.com}}</ref> Soviet/Russian space shuttle orbiter to be produced as part of the [[Buran program]]. It was never officially named. \n\n==History==\nConstruction of 2.02 is believed to began in 1988. The spacecraft belong to the second series orbiters, wich design has been improved considering experience of flight of K1 Buran<ref>http://www.buran.ru/galapago/NK2018-12_buran.pdf</ref>.\n\nBy 1993, when the Buran program was cancelled, orbiter 2.02 was in an early stage of construction (10-20 percent)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buran-energia.com/bourane-buran/bourane-modele-202.php|title=Buran Built models OK-2.02|website=www.buran-energia.com}}</ref>. Only forward fuselage with crew cabin was completed. The incomplete 2.02 was later partially dismantled at its construction site and moved to the outside of the Tushino Machine Building Plant, near Moscow.\n\nRight wing with landing gear produced for this orbiter was used to complete 0.01 test article, now on display at [[Exhibition_of_Achievements_of_National_Economy|VDNKh]]<ref>http://www.buran.ru/other/NK2012-06_p_70-71.pdf</ref> \n\nSome of the tiles from orbiter 2.02 were sold and auctioned on the [[Internet]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[Buran_program|Buran program]]\n* [[Spaceplane]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.buran-energia.com/bourane-buran/bourane-modele-202.php 2.02 orbiter]\n* [http://www.k26.com/buran/Future/2.02/space_buran_2_02.html 2.02 current status]\n\n{{Russian manned space programs}}\n{{Buran program}}\n{{Space Shuttles}}\n\n[[Category:Buran program]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Soviet spacecraft]]\n[[Category: Individual space vehicles]]\n\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BrainVE", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2.02_(Buran-class_spacecraft)"}
